===Verb===
{{en-verb||||past2=shore|shorn|past_ptc2=sheared}}

# To [[cut]], originally with a sword or other bladed weapon, now usually with [[shears]], or as if using shears.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1819|author=Walter Scott|title=Ivanhoe|passage=So trenchant was the Templar’s weapon, that it '''shore''' asunder, as it had been a willow twig, the tough and plaited handle of the mace, which the ill-fated Saxon reared to parry the blow, and, descending on his head, levelled him with the earth.}}
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Sonnets|sonnet=68|passage=the golden tresses {{...}} were '''shorn''' away}}
# To [[remove]] the [[fleece]] from a [[sheep]] etc. by [[clipping]].
#: {{ux|en|'''shear''' the llamas}}
# To [[cut]] the hair of (a person)
#: {{ux|en|'''shear''' the afro off someone's head}}
# {{lb|en|physics}} To [[deform]] because of forces pushing in opposite directions.
# {{lb|en|aviation|meteorology|intransitive}} (of wind) To change in direction and/or speed.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1985|author=[[w:National Transportation Safety Board|National Transportation Safety Board]]|title=Aircraft Accident Report: United Airlines Flight 663, Boeing 727-222, N7647U, Denver, Colorado, May 31, 1984|chapter=2.3: Airplane Takeoff Performance|url=https://libraryonline.erau.edu/online-full-text/ntsb/aircraft-accident-reports/AAR85-05.pdf|page=41|text=The total along-the-runway wind component '''sheared''' from an 8-knot headwind to about a 56-knot tailwind over a 44-second period.}}
# {{lb|en|mathematics}} To [[transform]] by [[displace|displacing]] every point in a [[direction]] [[parallel]] to some given [[line]] by a [[distance]] [[proportional]] to the point’s distance from the line.
# {{lb|en|mining|intransitive}} To make a [[vertical]] cut in [[coal]].
# {{lb|en|Scotland}} To [[reap]], as grain.
#: {{rfquotek|en|Jamieson}}
# {{lb|en|figurative}} To [[deprive]] of [[property]]; to [[fleece]].

